Program: R

Libraries used: dplyr glmnet cluster e1071 class caret MASS tree RColorBrewer randomForest

Introduction¶

The dataset that will be used contains information about prostate cancer. Each of the observation contains information on the type of cancer stage based on different attributes. In order to correctly identify the type of cancer stage the observation results to, different types of classification methods will be used.

Summary of the laboratory dataset:¶

The dataset contains 3000 observations of prostate cancer laboratory data. Of the 12 columns, 10 of the columns contain numerical feature of the cancer. The other 2 columns are the unique identifier (ID), in number, of each observations, and the other one is the result (result) of each observations, ranging from 0 to 3.

Attributes Data Types Comments

Result int Attribute is dependent, contains information on the result of the observation, ranging from 0 to 3. More information are shown below.

Dealing with the missing value¶

There are conventional methods to deal with missing value and that is to:

Deletion

This methods includes deleting the rows which contains the missing values. The advantage of this method is that it's quick and easy, it doesnt not require any computational methods. However the disadvantage is that valuable observations are lost. This case would work well if the missing values are missing completely at random (MCAR).

Imputation

There are two types if imputation, which is the mean imputation and the conditional mean imputation.

  • The normal mean imputation is computed based on the mean of the column, however this results in bias.

Given the formular f(y) = x1, x2, x3...xn

  • The conditional mean imputation uses other independent variables to estimate the value for the missing values. The rows that have complete case (complete information, no missing values) are used to regress X on all other independent variable, then using the estimated equation to predict for the missing x (missing value).
  • However some limitations to this method includes the underestimation of the standard error and the overestimation of the test statistics, where the value is determined completely by the model that was used and this results in a case where the standard error is ignored. In order to overcome this challenge, multiple imputation can be used. This includes doing multiple prediction of the missing value, adding additional form of error which is based on variations in the parameter estimates across the imputation (imputation error). Though multiple imputation will not be computed as it is not within the scope of what was studied.

Missing values analysis¶

NOTE: rows will be refered to as observations

Since the number of missing value is small the missing values can be estimated using the means of regression analysis (conditional imputation). Observation 1 and 4, contains one missing value (ATT1 and ATT4, respectively), however observation 3 contains two missing values (ATT3, ATT5). The pattern of missingness shows that the data are missing arbitrarily (cannot be ordered to observe a clear pattern).

Preparing the dataset for the regression analysis¶

Removing ID and result columns.¶

There are two different ways to determine the missing value through imputation, and some regression includes the use of the dependent variable (result) as well as other predictors, while some does not. [1] Explained that the dependent variable should not be used to train the mean regression model, [2] also stated the same, however some other articles such as [3] indicated that it should be used in imputation.

Imputation of the missing value explain¶

To impute the missing values, different regression models will be used. Since there are little to no relationshop between the predicting attributes and the resonse attribute, which is the value that is to be imputed, a linear regression model will not be used as the slope of it would be highly small, which would lead to odd values.

Benchmark Measurement¶

The mean square error (expected value for the square error loss) will be used as a benchmark measurement to determine which of the models will produce the most accurate value of the missing value.

The response variable will be the single column that contains the missing value. For example, in the first case of missing value, ATT1 contains missing value. All the other predictors beside ATT1 will be used as the predictor.

In order to solve the problem with using or not using the dependent variable, 'result', the variable will be included in the first prediction of the missing value, and determine which results in a lower MSE. Nevertheless, the redundant variable ID will be removed as it serves no purpose in prediction.

Creating test and training set¶

The complete case dataset will be randomized and split into test set and training set. The training set will contain 80% of the randomized dataset, shuffled and the other 20% is the randomized test set. This is so that the test error can be checked to reduce variance and bias of the model, and increase prediction accuracy.

Set Seed¶

Throughout the notebook, the set.seed(1234) will be used to ensure that the result produced is reproducible. However if the seed is not set or set to a different seed, it will produce a slightly different result but not significant

In [13]:
train_test <- function(dataset, response){
    set.seed(1234)
    sub <- sample(nrow(dataset), floor(nrow(dataset) * 0.8)) # choose only 80% of the of the dataset
    if(response == 'train'){return(dataset[sub, ])} # returns train which contains 80% of the shuffled data
    else if(response == 'test'){return(dataset[-sub, ])} # returns test, contains 20% of the shuffled data
}

Building a model to predict missing value¶

There are numerous of regressions that can be used to predict the missing values. The regressions includes, but not limited to, lasso and ridge regression, through applying regularization term regression and the regression tree.

Lasso and Ridge

Both lasso and ridge are similar, they penalised the coefficients of each variables by adding a degree of bias. This results to small coefficient values in predictors that are likely to be redundant for ridge, but for lasso it penalises redundant predictors to 0, essentially removing it. These methods reduces standard error, however for ridge it does not reduce model complexity, however lasso does when it makes certain attribute have the coefficients of 0.

Regression tree

Decision tree can be used for classification and prediction purposes. The tree will be used as it is a non-linear model, to predict the missing value of the four attributes. Tree works by splitting the top of the tree into terminal nodes/leaves.

Logistic regression

Lastly a simple logistic regression is similar to linear regression, however it can only be used for binary values, (0 or 1, yes or no etc) as it is used to determine the probability of success and failure. Hence, it cannot be used to predict the missing values within each attributes as the values are discrete numerical.

Function - calculate MSE of the model and predict missing value using ridge and lasso¶

In [17]:
ridge_lass <- function(train, test, var, o_l, pred_set, response){
    variable <- as.formula(paste(var, '~.')) # paste variable with ~.
    train_mat <- model.matrix(variable, data = train)[,-1] # create matrix for the data
    test_mat <- model.matrix(variable, data = test)[, -1]
    
    fit_ridge <- glmnet(train_mat, train[[var]], alpha = o_l) # fit ridge/lasso regression on the dataset
    cv_ridge <- cv.glmnet(train_mat, train[[var]], alpha = o_l)
    
    if(response == 'mean'){
        pred_ridge <- predict(fit_ridge, s = cv_ridge$lambda.1se, newx = test_mat) # predict the value using best lamda
        mean_ss <- mean((pred_ridge - test[[var]])^2) # determine mean square error
        return(mean_ss)
    } else if(response == 'value'){  
        test_mat2 <- model.matrix(variable, 
                              model.frame(~ ., pred_set, na.action = na.pass))[,-1] 
        response <- predict(cv_ridge, test_mat2, s = "lambda.1se")
        return(response) # return the predicted values
    }
}

However, when result was included, it resulted in a mean square error as shown in the table below. In [24]:
selection_model <- function(train_set, test_set, var, pred_set, response){
    set.seed(1234)
    ridge <- ridge_lass(train_set, test_set, var, 0, pred_set, 'mean')
    ridge_val <- ridge_lass(train_set, test_set, var, 0, pred_set, 'value')
    
    set.seed(1234)
    lasso <- ridge_lass(train_set, test_set, var, 1, pred_set, 'mean')
    lasso_val <- ridge_lass(train_set, test_set, var, 1, pred_set, 'value')
    
    if(response == 'rval'){return(ridge_val)}
    else if(response == 'lval'){return(lasso_val)}
    else if(response == 'mse'){return(cat('The MSE for ridge is', ridge, ', the MSE for lasso is', lasso))}
}

Predicting missing value in ATT3 and ATT5¶

There are two missing values in row 3. The regression models can only predict and impute 1 value. In order to predict both value, the mathematic process called 'Substitution by Elimination' will be used.

In this process, one of the attribute column will be removed and the model will be trained on the remaining attribute, to predict the missing value of the column that was not remove. SO in this case, Column ATT5 will be removed and the model will be trained on the remaining columns to predict ATT3. Once ATT3 is found, it will then be substituted in, then that column will be used along wit the rest to predict ATT5.

Task 2: Classification¶

According to the Australian Government, there are 18,138 [5] of males with prostate cancer. Therefore it is important to classify the stages of prostate cancer when given observations. The result contains information based on the cancer stage.As seen in the data set, there are 4 classes that classify each of the varaibles. These being 0, 1, 2 and 3 indicating the four stages of cancer:

  • 0: Curable
  • 1: Tumour stage
  • 2: Node stage and
  • 3: Incurable cancers

    Being a supervised learning dataset, different classification methods can be implemented to understand these four classes used to seperate the data sets. In order to identify the most appropriate method of classification, 4 techniques have been implemented to learn from the data provided:
    i. Decision Trees (Classification)
    ii. Linear and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis
    iii. Support Vector Machines
    iv. K Nearest Neighbors (KNN)

Converting the datatype¶

Currently, the result column datatype is 'int' however this has to be converted to factor as it is a qualitative cancer level between 0 and 3 as previously indicated.

2.1 Decision Trees¶

Type of decision tree for the prostate cancer laboratory dataset¶

There are different types of decision tree, namely Categorical Variable Decision Tree and Continous Variable Decision Tree:

Categorical Variable Decision Tree - Has categorical response variable like cancer result ()

Continous Variable Decision - Has continous target variable

Previously, for the purpose of imputing the missing values in the a data set provided a regression tree was used. However, in the case of the response variable being categorical, a classification tree is used. The tree follows a top-down greedy approach known as the 'recursive binary split'.

The decision tree segregates the observations based on all values of the attributes and determines which of the attribute creates the best homogenous set of observations. Hence, it splits the node on all variables, then select the splits that resulted in most homogenous sub-nodes.

In the case of a regression tree, the residual sum square was used as a criterion to split the tree. In classifcation tree, however, there are various types of algorithm that are used here for the categorical case. It is worth noting that the two approaches are sensitive to node purity.

  • Gini Index

  • Cross-entropy

Tree or pruned tree is not suitable for the classification of result¶

CART (Classification And Regression Tree), is refered to as the descision tree algorithm. The R libraries, 'tree' and uses the concept of CART and this library will be used to grow the tree.

calculate_missclas <- function(prediction, variable){
    acc <- (1 - mean(prediction != variable)) * 100
    return(acc)
}

Bagging¶

To construct a more powerful classification model, bagging, as the building block to trees will be used. Boostrapping can be used can be used in a different context with tree to improve the tree based learning methods. Tree usually suffer from high variance. Originally the tree is split into two halves, resulting in a case where the two halves produce different result. To reduce variance, Bagging is used to take repeated samples from the training data to generate ith different training datasets, then the model can be trained on all these datasets.

The tree are grown deep on these new training dataset and not pruned, resulting in each of these individual tree having high variance but low bias. The average is taken, hence reducing the variance.

In [44]:

                        ntree = 100, proximity = TRUE) # running bagged tree

Out-of-Bag error estimation¶

Using the OOB approach, the tree did not need to be cross-validated, since bagging uses the concept of bootstrap and the tree are repeatedly fit to its subset. Each bagged tree uses 2/3 of the observations and the other 1/3 that was not used to fit the tree to predict the response. This is virtually equivalent to the concept of 'leave one out' cross validation error. The OOB error rate was computed on the training data set, which resulted in 26.58%, therefore there a likelihood of the bagging model accuracy to be 73.42% using 100 tree.

Summary bagging result¶

The classification accuracy for the bagging descision tree is 100% when predicting it on the training data. This is likely to be the case as more tree are created and grown deep without pruning. Although only 100 tree was used, it produced a classification accuracy of 76% for on the testing data. Also, the error rate using the test data resulted in a lower rate than the OOB estimation. Although with any bagging or random forest, the number of tree is notthe critical parameter, a descision tree bagging plot was still graphed to depict the error rate using different number of tree, at 100 and 1000.

Description of tree graph¶

Using using 100 tree it showed that the classification error rate for cancer result 0, 1 and 2 are decreasing as the number of tree increases, however for the result 3, it increases as the number of tree increases. This showed that as the number of tree increases, classifying a result of 3 becomes more difficult, where the error rate is expected to rise over 80%. Using 1000 tree, it showed that the error rate for result 3 was higher than 80% after 200 tree. Nevertheless, all the other cancerous result error rate plateued after 200 tree, at an error rate that is less than 45%, almost half the error rate for the result 3.

Random Forest¶

Random forest uses the same concept a bagging, and that is using bootstrap to lower the variance. However it is an improvement over bagged tree as it decorrelates the trees. It does this through specificying certain values of predictors it should look at. Originally, when building a bagged tree the algorithm looks at a majority of available predictors and uses the strongest predictor, this causes all bagged tree to look similar to one another and the predictions to be highly correlated. As the reduction of the variance of uncorrelated tree is better than correlated tree, random forest uncorrelates the tree by forcing each split to consider only a subset of the predictors. In general case, the square root of the predictor is used as the paramter for mtry.

Building random forest¶

The random tree will be built using 100 tree first then 1000 tree. Nevertheless the number of predictors that will lead in both a reduction in the test error and OOB error is the square root of the number of predictors.

In [48]:

Upon looking at the shape of the boxplot, bagged tree is slightly skewewed, whereas random forest is uniformed, this is due to the uncorrelation between each attributes. The importance of ATT6 is in the middle in bagged tree, which shows that is is somewhat correlated with other attributes, as when the correlation of it was removed, it became the least important in random forest.

Choosing random forest¶

Since random forest removed the correlation, which reduces the variance within the data, and have a higher classification accuracy than bagged tree, random forest is a better classifer in this case. Hence, random forest will be used as a descision tree to classify the result of the cancer.


2.2 Discriminant Analysis¶

Why Disriminant Analysis¶

First and foremost as there are more than two response classes linear discriminant analysis is usually the more preferred and popular method utilized with dealing with such a classification problem. Thus, linear discriminant analysis is ofen used as an alternative to logistic regression. In logistical regression we model the conditional distribution of the response $Y$, given a set of predictors $X$. However, in disriminant analyis the distribution of the predictors $X$ are modelled seperately in each of the response classes given $Y$ and use Baye's theorem to find the esitmates for finding the probablility that $Y$ belongs to a certain class $k$, given $X$=$x$. It does this by finding the linear combination of predictors that both maximizes the separation between the centers of the data and minimizes the variation within each group.

Parameters are estimated and then used in the Bayes classifier. The Bayes classifier assigns each observation to the most likely class given its predictor values. Essentially linear discriminant analysis is a classifier that attempts to approximate the Bayes classifier

Below, we will run the linear discriminant analysis with the imputed values.

Cross validation¶

We now have produced a model based on Linear Discriminant Analysis. However, as is usual the training error often underestimates the actual test error rate. For this reason, we will run the model with cross-validation parameter set to true. The MASS library utilised for performing the LDA makes use of Leave One Out Cross Validaion or LOOCV. Generally, the test error is estimating by holding out a subset of the training observations from the fitting process, and then applying the statistical learning method, in this case LDA, to the held out observations. More specifically, in LOOCV, the LDA model is fit on to $n-1$ training observations and classification is made on the excluded observation. The LOOCV estimate for the prediction accuracy is thus an average of the preictive accuracies.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis¶

We now shift our focus to trying to attempt classify the results of the observation using quadratic discriminant analysis. Similar to LDA quadratic discriminant analysis assumes that the observations are drawn from a Gaussian distribution. As mentioned earlier, LDA assumes a class-specific mean vector and a covariance matrix that is common to all $K$ classes. This is where the main difference between LDA and QDA arises. Unlike linear discriminant analyis, quadratic discriminant analysis relaxes common covariance assumption in LDA and assumes that each class has a unique covariance matrix.

As in the case of LDA we will utilize the MASS package to produce a QDA model hown below.

As observed previously, QDA produced a classification accuracy of 97% whereas LDA produced classification accuracy of approximately 95%. This is in concurrence with the table produced above which portrays the various sensitivities for each class given the method used. We can see that the sensitivity produced by QDA for every class with the exception of Class 1 is higher - thus accounting for the higher classification accuracy of QDA.

As discussed earlier, linear discriminant analysis assumes that the observations are drawn from a multivariate Gaussian distribution and have a common covariance matrix amongst all the classes $K$. In contrast, QDA assumes relaxes this assumption and assumes that the classes have unique covariance matrices. This underlying assumption of LDA is thus much less of flexible of a classifier than QDA - as there are only $Kp$ linear coefficients to be estimated. As a result, LDA has a substantially lower variance than its QDA counter part and this could potentially lead to improved predictive performance. However, this was not the case with the prostate cancer data set used. The QDA model - with its quadratic decision boundaries- has outperformed the LDA.

It is likely that the classes do not share a common covariance matrix and the Bayesian decision boundary is quadratic rather than linear. It is for this reason that the QDA has more accurately approximated this boundary this yielding superior prediction accuracy than its linear counterpart.

2.3 Classification by SVM¶

The Support Vector Machine (SVM) is used when classification of data with multiple classes, i.e. more than two classes is required. SVM uses the all-vs-all classification approach when more than two classes in the response variable have been detected. Using a kernel that allows soft vector classification, i.e. allowing a certain limit of misclassification, data of massive sets with different classes can be seperated using the support vectors for the hyper plane. This can be done either linearly by using the linear kernel or non-linearly, by using the radial or the polynomial kernel. The value of cost define the threshold of misclassification permitted and for the radial kernel, value of gamma is used to specify the radial basis. These misclassification vectors are tuned to select the best when it comes to fitting the SVM on the training data set. Since the data set is supervised, a confusion matrix to test the prediction accuracy can be implemented.

We create the train and test data sets needed for the models.

a. Using Linear Kernel¶

The linear kernel measures for the similarity between the variables and accordingly outputs the support vector classifier. Using a fine tuned value for cost (i.e. the margin for misclassification), the tune() cross validates the range of input given using the K Fold cross validation technique and outputs the best cost value to be used. The smaller the cost value, the larger the number of support vectors.

b. Radial Kernel¶

The radial kernel for SVM is used to classify data in a non-linear fashion. This kernel looks works locally by pedicting the class for the test variable by the local surrounding training observation, and not those farther away. The radial kernel uses a gamma value as a positive constant to seperate the observations non-linearly. This gamma value can also be tuned with the cost function, in order to obtain the most optimal value.

c. Polynomial Kernel¶

The polynomial kernel is another form of a non-linear kernel for SVM which helps produce a flexible boundary for the classifiers. Instead of quantifying the similarity of 2 variables with a single power creating a rigid boundary for the variables, raising the kernel to the power of a higher number (not more than 4, to avoid over-fitting), the margin boundaries are made flexible enough to accomodate non-linear data. We test the classification using the polynomial kernel on the data set provided.

In order to conduct a polynomial kernel classification, two degrees of the kernel are tested: polynomial of degree 2 and of degree 3. This is done in order to understand and select the best degree that can be used. Using a polynomial of degree over 4 would end up in over fitting, which needs to be avoided.
The tune() is used to select the best cost value for the kernel, allowing a certain amount of misclassification.

In [71]:
# Tune kernel to get cost values for the degree 2
tune.out.2 <- tune(svm, Result ~ ., data = train_data, kernel = "polynomial", degree = 2, ranges = list(cost = 10^seq(-2, 1, by = 0.25)))

The table above shows the different kernels used for SVM and their prediction accuracies based on the test data. The Linear Kernel produces a perfect prediction accuracy which is not desirable. This indicates overfitting. Thus, this kernel method is ruled out. The Radial Kernel on the other hand produces a very low prediction accurary as compared to the other two with more than two thirds of the variables as support vectors. This displays very low variance and very high bias, which again is undesirable. Thus, Radial Kernel too is ruled out. Comparatively, the polynomial kernel is the best as compared to the other two kernels. Thus, for this particular data set, the Polynomial Kernel of degree 3 is accepted as the best support vector machine.

2.4. KNN Classification¶

Another method of classification that could be considered for a multi-class data set is the K Nearest Neighbours, otherwise known as KNN, where the test observation is allotted to a specific class based on the probabilities of the class of k nearest training observations. In order to learn more from the classification of the cancer data set, KNN is implemented by splitting the data to a train set, a test set and a target class set that contains the Result column.

In [81]:
# Creating train set
knn_train <- train_test(new_data, 'train')
# Creating test set
knn_test <- train_test(new_data, 'test')
# Target variable train set
knn_target_train <- knn_train$Result
# Target variable test set
knn_target_test <- knn_test$Result

knn_train <- subset(knn_train, select = -Result)
knn_test <- subset(knn_test, select = -Result)

The value of K determines the number of training observations that will be considered as nearest neighbours. As a rule of thumb, the value can be the square root of the number of observations. Using this rule, the value of K is set accordingly for the knn().

In [82]:
# Value of K set by the square root of the total number of observations, which is 3000
k <- sqrt(nrow(new_data))
# Rounding off the value of K to the upper bound
ceiling(k)
55

The odd value of K will help in eliminating any possibilities of a tie. Using this value of k, the model is fit

In [83]:
# Fitting the KNN model on the test data using the training observations for 55 nearest neighbors
knn_model <- knn(train = knn_train, test = knn_test, cl = knn_target_train, k)
# Compare the predicted values with the original target test
confusionMatrix(knn_target_test, knn_model)

Model Selection¶

What follows is a discussion of the two competing models that we have assumed to be most appropriate for the classification task at hand. It is important to note that the discussion of SVM with a polynomial kernes as well as both types of discriminant analysis has been limited to the previous section only. The underlying reason is that first, the SVM model produced has generated a classification accuracy of 100% for radial and linear kernel. Furthermore the polynomial kernel has the tendency of being computationally inefficient and thus was not considered. With regards to the discriminant analysis - both linear and quadratic - the classifiaction accuracy was 95% and 97% respecitively, and in our opinion this poses the potential of overfitting. The two competing models discussed below are thus the KNN model and the Random Forest with their respective advantages and disadvantages.

1. K Nearest Neighbors¶

Advantages The advanatge of using KNN is that it does not assume the class of the test variable, rather it is classified based on the neighboring training values and their corresponding classes. KNN only worries about the local neighbors for each training value and thus calculated the distance for local neighbors/variables alone

Disadvantages In order to conduct the classifications on each of the test varaibles, the value of K needs to be determined. An incorrect selection of the K value can throw the bias-variance of the classification trade-off off balance. Also, the calculation of the distances between two neighbors will be computationally expensive if the training data is big. Thus, bigger the training set, slower is the computation time. KNN is very sensitive to outliers, or misclassified training variables and can end up misclassifying the individual test variables.

2. Random Forest¶

Adavantages Random has a lot of advantages and one of it is that it is a non-parametric method, hence there is no need to worry about the dataset having outliers, however one of the major advantage is that the dataset does not have to be linearly seperable. The laboratory dataset does not have any correlation, hence this dataset is suitable as it has no linear or any noticable correlations. One major advantage of Random forest is that it uses the concept of boostrap to reduce variance while maintaining the same bias, hence there are no bias and variance tradeoff.

Disadvantages One major disadvantage of random forest is that when there are few tree, it is prone to overfit to the noise of the dataset. Hence if there are lots of noise rather than signal in the dataset, random forest cannot handle it well. Due to this the dataset has to not have large number of irrelevant features. As more tree are added, the tendency to overfit decreases, however has a trade off with computational time. Hence, growing the tree is rather slow compared to other methods, that is, when ntree is relatively large.

Comparison between the models¶

SVM produced a classification accuracy of 100%, therefore it showed that this is likely to be an overfittiing model. This is also similar case with QDA. Hence, only K Nearest Neighbors and Random Forest are acceptable at this stage. When comparing the two model's classification accuracy, Random Forest classification accuracy of 78.17% and the KNN prodcued an accuracy of 79.83%. Although the two accuracy are close, with KNN having a slightly advantage, the Random Forest will be used instead. The problem with KNN is that as the value of K increases it has a trade off between bias and variance, where variance would decrease but bias increase. However with random forest, as the number of tree increases, variance decreases however there is no bias to variance tradeoff. The advantage of random forest is that the bias of it remains the same as it was when it was a single tree, hence increasing the number of tree, which consequently also decreases the variance does not increase bias.
